"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"Cir 1345–1399":"1345–1399","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1353–Male":"1353–Deceased","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1357–Male":"1357–Deceased","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1370–1485":"1370–1485","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","after 4 March 1368":"after 4 March 1368","Cir 1345":"1345","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","1368":"1368","1357":"1357","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1353":"1353","Loudoun Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudoun Castle, Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudon, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Campbell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir George Campbell was born in 1345, in Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Andrew Campbell - Tenth Lord of Loudon, was 35 and his mother, Campbell, was 26. He married Margaret de Berkeley in 1372, in Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1399, in his hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"Cir 1345–1399":"1345–1399","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1370–1485":"1370–1485","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","after 4 March 1368":"pärast 4. märtsi 1368","Cir 1345":"1345","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","1368":"1368","1357":"1357","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1353":"1353","Loudoun Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudoun Castle, Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudon, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Cir 1345–1399":"1345–1399","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1357–Male":"1357–Kuollut","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1370–1485":"1370–1485","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","after 4 March 1368":"4. maaliskuuta 1368 jälkeen","